**Example 6**

A horizontal plate is vibrating vertically with simple harmonic motion at a frequency of 20 Hz as shown in the diagram.

What is the maximum amplitude of vibration so that fine sand on the plate always remains in contact with it?

The restoring force on the sand is the resultant force acting on it. It acts towards the equilibrium position. Therefore

\[N-mg =ma\] \[N-mg =m(-\omega^{2}x)\] \[N =mg-mo^{2}x\]

For the sand to remain in contact with the plate, the normal contact force \(N\) should be more than 0:

\[N > 0\] \[mg-mo^{2}x > 0\] \[x < \frac{g}{\omega^{2}}\] \[x < \frac{g}{\left(2\pi f\right)^{2}}=\frac{9.81}{\left(2\pi\left(20 \right)\right)^{2}}=0.00062\text{ m}\]

Hence the maximum value of \(x\) is 0.62 mm.

The amplitude of vibration must be at most 0.62 mm for the sand to always remain in contact with the plate.

