## Definition List

\begin{tabular}{|p{346.9pt}|p{346.9pt}|} \hline Oscillation & An oscillation is a periodic to-and-fro motion of an object between two limits. \\ \hline Free oscillations & Oscillating system where there is no energy gain or loss (no external force acting on the system). \\ \hline Forced oscillations & Forced oscillations are caused by continual input of energy by external applied force to an oscillating system to compensate the loss due to damping in order to _maintain_ the amplitude of the oscillation. \\ \hline Damped oscillations & Oscillation in which there is a continuous dissipation of energy to the surroundings such that the total energy in the system decreases with time, hence the amplitude of the motion progressively decreases with time. \\ \hline Equilibrium position & Equilibrium position (or neutral position) is the position at which no _net_ force acts on the oscillating mass. \\ \hline Simple Harmonic motion (SHM) & Simple harmonic motion is defined as oscillatory motion of a particle whose acceleration is directly proportional to its displacement from a fixed point and this acceleration is always in opposite direction to its displacement. \\ \hline _Angular frequency (\(\omega\))_ & _Angular frequency (\(\omega\))_ of an oscillation refers to the constant which characterizes the particular simple harmonic oscillator and is related to its natural frequency \(f\) given by \(\omega=2\,\pi\). Unit: radians per second (rad s\({}^{-1}\)). \\ \hline _Frequency (\(\bar{f}\))_ & Frequency is the number of complete to-and-fro cycles per unit time made by the oscillating object. Unit: Hertz. \\ \hline _Period (\(T\))_ & Period (\(T\)) is the time taken for one complete oscillation. Unit: second. \\ \hline Phase & An angle in either degrees or radians which gives a measure of the fraction of a cycle that has been completed by an oscillating particle or by a wave. \\ \hline Phase difference (2010) & Phase difference is a measure of how much one wave is out of step with another. It is measured in either degrees or radians. \\ \hline Displacement & Displacement is the distance of the oscillating mass from its equilibrium position at any instant in a stated direction. \\ \hline Amplitude & Amplitude is the maximum displacement of the oscillating mass from the equilibrium position. \\ \hline Damping & Damping is a process where energy is taken from an oscillating system as a result of dissipative forces. \\ \hline Natural Frequency & A system that is free to vibrate will vibrate at its natural frequency when no external force acting on it. Natural frequency depends on its dimensions and nature of material. \\ \hline Resonance (2005) & Resonance occurs when the resulting amplitude of the system becomes a maximum when the driving frequency of external driving force equals to natural frequency of the system. At resonance, there is a maximum transfer of energy from the driving system to the driven system. \\ \hline Shape of frequency response graph of damped oscillation (2005) & \(\bullet\) Lower peak \(\bullet\) Flatter peak \(\bullet\) Peak occurs at lower frequency than (shifts leftwards slightly from) natural frequency \(\bullet\) Smaller amplitude at _all_ frequencies \\ \hline \end{tabular}

